CROSS-EXAMINATION TRANSCRIPT EXCERPT
Witness: Mr. Ramesh Kumar Sharma (Project Manager, Claimant)
Cross-examined by: Counsel for RMSCL

Q: Did you give written notice for the site possession delay on Day-1 (10.05.2024)?
A: Yes, we sent a written letter dated 11.05.2024 by Speed Post and also sent emails.

Q: Do you have the email acknowledgement from RMSCL?
A: We have the sent-box copies. RMSCL did not formally acknowledge receipt.

Q: Is email a valid notice under the contract?
A: Yes. The contract allows email as an acceptable mode of communication.
   (Counsel note: Check contract clause — if contract requires registered post, email alone may be challenged.)

Q: You said 150 workers were at site from 10.05.2024 — can you produce their attendance?
A: Yes, the labour register for May 2024 is Exhibit C-8.

Q: Were these workers specifically deployed for this project or shared with other projects?
A: Exclusively for this project. Their gate-entry register confirms this.

Q: The machine idle cost you claim — are these owned machines or hired?
A: Mix of both. The tower crane (owned), JCBs (hired from M/s. Garg Machinery, Udaipur).

Q: Do you have hire receipts for the JCBs for the idle period?
A: Yes — Exhibit C-14 to C-18 are the hired machinery invoices.

Re-Examination by Claimant's Advocate:
Q: Despite emails and letters, did RMSCL respond to your complaints about idle resources?
A: No written response was received for 45 days. The site engineer verbally asked us to wait.

[Adverse inference against RMSCL: Employer failed to respond to contractor's notice of idle resources,
 implying acknowledgment of the delay — per Kesoram Industries precedent.]
